                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65801"><name nymRef="#Τιμάνωρ">Τιμάνωρ</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65363"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Πολύβωλος">Πολυβώλω</name></persName></persName>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                 <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Timanôr fils de Polybôlos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Timanor son of Polybolos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Timanor figlio di Polybolos.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The stone comes evidently from a Necropolis, although we do not know which one. It has been re-used twice on other sides.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
